215	https://stellifivc.substack.com/p/housing-affordability-in-todays-market	Housing Affordability in Today's Market	Using Homeownership as a Measure of Stability	<html><head></head><body><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg" width="1456" height="1188" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1188,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:678344,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><h6><em>Image from ‚ÄúMedian U.S. Home Prices and Housing Affordability by State‚Äù (howmuch.net)</em></h6><p></p><p><strong>Homeownership as a Measure of Stability                                                </strong>Homeownership has long been a key measure of the strength of the middle-class and upward mobility. At the core of this belief is that homeownership has historically been a wealth generator. As far back as we can measure, property owners have benefited from property appreciation as long as they‚Äôve held the property long enough. With homeownership increasingly out of reach for the average American, affordable housing has become a high-priority issue in the national discussion. But there‚Äôs an inherent conflict in this discussion: It‚Äôs impossible to provide affordable housing, and at the same time have that housing be a wealth generator for the owner.</p><p><strong>Government Subsidized Housing                                                                              </strong>Painting with broad strokes, there are two ways to create affordable housing: the government can subsidize housing, or we can increase supply in proportion to demand. When people refer to affordable housing, they usually mean government subsidized housing - that is rental homes or apartments financed with the help of local housing authorities, tax abatements or tax credits. This type of housing offers a lower rent burden, but it also prevents lower and lower to middle-class earners from participating in arguably the best wealth-generating asset for Americans.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Increasing Supply                                                                                                         </strong>Another way to widen the homeowner pool and promote wealth creation through asset ownership is through increasing the supply of housing. In practice, this can mean a lot of things: lower interest rates, removing red tape, and new housing production technologies ‚Äì all of these things would help increase supply by making it faster and cheaper to build housing. But in the long-run, if we did this effectively, this ‚Äúnaturally affordable housing‚Äù would not be the wealth generator that we think of today.</p><p><strong>We‚Äôre Betting on Efficiency                                                                                           </strong>Which direction the country moves on the issues will be, in large part, determined by policy decisions yet to be made. The one throughline that we see is efficiency. No matter which path we take, efficiency will be key. By taking advantage of advancements in PropTech, software, and the real estate market expansion, these new, innovative solutions could be leveraged to create new opportunities for affordable housing that don‚Äôt rely on government intervention and subsidies.</p></body></html>	The article discusses the conflict between providing affordable housing and housing as a wealth generator. It explores two approaches: government subsidized housing and increasing housing supply.	2024-10-22 22:59:53	2024-10-26 13:35:07.628	2024-10-26 14:01:31.563	{vc}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff0dbee10-9b33-4d57-afdf-79225878d6c2_1600x1305.jpeg	Gilberto Orozco	housing-affordability-in-todays
