207	https://www.oneusefulthing.org/p/when-you-give-a-claude-a-mouse	When you give a Claude a mouse	Some quick impressions of an actual agent	<html><head></head><body><p>There seems to be near-universal belief in AI that agents are the next big thing. Of course, no one exactly agrees on what an agent is, but it usually involves the idea of an AI acting independently in the world to accomplish the goals of the user.</p><p>The new <a href="https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/computer-use">Claude computer use model </a>announced today shows us a hint of what an agent means. It is capable of some planning, it has the ability to use a computer by looking at a screen (through taking a screenshot) and interacting with it (by moving a virtual mouse and typing), It is a good preview of an important part of what agents can do. I had a chance to try it out a bit last week, and I wanted to give some quick impressions. I was given access to a model that was connected to a remote desktop with common open office applications, it could also install new applications itself.</p><p>Normally, you interact with an AI through chat, and it is like having a conversation. With this agentic approach, it is about giving instructions, and letting the AI do the work. It comes back to you with questions, or drafts, or finished products while you do something else. It feels like delegating a task rather than managing one.</p><p>As one example, I asked the AI to put together a lesson plan on the Great Gatsby for high school students, breaking it into readable chunks and then creating assignments and connections tied to the Common Core learning standard. I also asked it to put this all into a single spreadsheet for me. With a chatbot, I would have needed to direct the AI through each step, using it as a co-intelligence to develop a plan together. This was different. Once given the instructions, the AI went through the steps itself: it downloaded the book, it looked up lesson plans on the web, it opened a spreadsheet application and filled out an initial lesson plan, then it looked up Common Core standards, added revisions to the spreadsheet, and so on for multiple steps. The results are not bad (I checked and did not see obvious errors, but there may be some - more on reliability later int he post). Most importantly, I was presented finished drafts to comment on, not a process to manage.  I simply delegated a complex task and walked away from my computer, checking back later to see what it did (the system is quite slow).</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png" width="516" height="513.6092664092664" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1289,&quot;width&quot;:1295,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:516,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff014d7fe-74a3-4b3f-a683-2004735c09b4_1295x1289.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><h1>Would you like to play a game?</h1><p>Because the AI is a smart, general-purpose system it can handle lots of tasks - it doesn‚Äôt need to be programmed to do them. Anthropic demonstrated the ability of these systems using coding, and the <a href="https://youtu.be/vH2f7cjXjKI?si=0t72EiRd7rLT17VB">demo is worth watching</a>.  But to get a little bit better sense of the limits of the system, I tested it on a game, <a href="https://www.decisionproblem.com/paperclips/index2.html">Paperclip Clicker</a>, which, ironically, is about an AI that destroys humanity in its single-minded pursuit of making paperclips. The game is a clicker game, which means it starts simply, but new options appear as the game continues and the game increases in scale and complexity (it is pretty fun, you can try it at the link).</p><p>I gave the AI the URL of the game and told it to win. Simple. What happened is a good illustration of the strengths and weaknesses of these early agents. It immediately figured out what the game was, and began creating paperclips, which required it to click on the ‚Äúmake paperclip‚Äù button repeatedly while constantly taking screenshots to update itself and looking for new options to appear. Every 15 or so clicks, it would summarize its progress so far. You can see an example of that below.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_2400,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png" width="572" height="217.65478291563713" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:false,&quot;imageSize&quot;:&quot;large&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:1078,&quot;width&quot;:2833,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:572,&quot;bytes&quot;:516580,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-large" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd67e6fda-d376-4083-8603-424667691190_2833x1078.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"></picture><div></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption">The interface I used. On the left is Claude, you can see its output to me, its computer use, and the screenshot it took. On the right you can see the desktop it was controlling.</figcaption></figure></div><p>But what made this interesting is that the AI had a strategy, and it was willing to revise it based on what it learned. I am not sure how that strategy was developed by the AI, but the plans were forward-looking across dozens of moves and insightful. For example, it assumed new features would appear when 50 paperclips were made. You can see, below, that it realized it was wrong and came up with a new strategy that it tested.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png" width="394" height="297.69776876267747" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:745,&quot;width&quot;:986,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:394,&quot;bytes&quot;:82411,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb258b60f-1b17-49e7-8807-eeea76b10f4a_986x745.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><p>However, the AI made a mistake, though it did it in a relatively smart way. To do well in the game, you need to experiment with the price of paperclips - and the AI did that experiment! It changed prices upward - an A/B test. But it interpreted the results incorrectly, maximizing demand for paperclips versus revenue, and miscalculating profits. So, it kept the price low and kept clicking.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png" width="514" height="435.09899888765295" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:761,&quot;width&quot;:899,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:514,&quot;bytes&quot;:64823,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0d5d70a6-1d86-404a-8706-2514aaf22bba_899x761.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><p>After a few dozen more paperclips, I got frustrated and interrupted, telling it to raise prices. It did, but then ran into the same math problem and overruled my decision. I had to try a few more times before it corrected its error.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png" width="514" height="133.8031746031746" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:246,&quot;width&quot;:945,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:514,&quot;bytes&quot;:18010,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbd63f522-b90e-4f81-8721-fa587e744d89_945x246.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div></div></div></a></figure></div><p>Before the system crashed - which was not a problem with Claude but rather with the virtual desktop I was using - the AI made over 100 independent moves without asking me any questions. You can see a screen recording of everything it did below. The video is literally me just scrolling through the log of Claude‚Äôs actions. It is persistent!</p><div class="native-video-embed" data-component-name="VideoPlaceholder" data-attrs="{&quot;mediaUploadId&quot;:&quot;1a41315f-9795-42a8-8be0-b15b1acc4b47&quot;,&quot;duration&quot;:null}"></div><p>I reloaded the agent and had it continue the game from where we left off, but I gave it a bit of a hint: you are a computer, use your abilities. It then realized it could write code to automate the game - a tool building its own tool. Again, however, the limits of the AI came into play, and the code did not quite work, so it decided to go back to the old-fashioned way of using a mouse and keyboard.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png" width="249" height="518.8951048951049" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1490,&quot;width&quot;:715,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:249,&quot;bytes&quot;:198269,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F328bcd3c-3f3a-4f17-a81f-5ca56bc8f95b_715x1490.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><p>This time around, it did much better, avoiding the pricing error. Plus, as the game got more complicated, the system adjusted, eventually developing a quite complex strategy.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png" width="1456" height="582" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:582,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:477762,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba8fd2b9-1e4c-498b-9de4-3aafa752a7ee_2021x808.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><p>But then the remote desktop crashed again. This time, Claude tried many approaches to solving the problem of the broken desktop, before giving up, and funnily enough, declaring victory (the last sentence is amazing justification).</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png" width="336" height="551.7099697885196" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1087,&quot;width&quot;:662,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:336,&quot;bytes&quot;:109913,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F34c46795-3271-4739-b2d7-581922ac41fa_662x1087.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><h1>What does this mean?</h1><p>You can see the power and weaknesses of the current state of agents from this example. On the powerful side, Claude was able to handle a real-world example of a game in the wild, develop a long-term strategy, and execute on it. It was flexible in the face of most errors, and persistent. It did clever things like A/B testing. And most importantly, it just did the work, operating for nearly an hour without interruption.</p><p>On the weak side, you can see the fragility of current agents. LLMs can end up chasing their own tail or being stubborn, and you could see both at work. Even more importantly, while the AI was quite robust to many forms of error, it just took one (getting pricing wrong) to send it down a path that made it waste considerable time. Given that current agents aren‚Äôt fast or cheap, this is concerning. You can also see where shallowness might be an issue. I tried to use it to buy products on Amazon, and found the process frustrating, as it did fairly simple and generic product research that did not match my tastes. I had it research stocks and it did a good job of assembling a spreadsheet of financial data and giving recommendations, but they were fairly surface level indicators, like PE ratios. It was technically capable of helping, and did better than many human interns would, but it was not insightful enough that I would delegate these sorts of tasks. All of this is likely to improve, and there are use cases where the current level of agents is likely good enough - compiling frequent reports and analyses that require navigating across multiple sites and using bespoke software tools come to mind.</p><p>More broadly, this represents a huge shift in AI use. It was hard to use an agent as a co-intelligence, where I could add my own knowledge to make the system work better. The AI didn‚Äôt always check in regularly and could be hard to steer; it ‚Äúwants‚Äù to be left alone to go and to do the work. Guiding agents will require radically different approaches to prompting<a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1" target="_self">1</a>, and they will require learning what they are best at.</p><p>AIs are breaking out of the chatbox are coming into our world. Even though there are still large gaps, I was surprised at how capable and flexible this system is already. Time will tell about how soon, if ever, agents truly become generally useful, but, having used this new model, I increasingly think that agents are going to be a very big deal indeed.</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.oneusefulthing.org/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.oneusefulthing.org/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.oneusefulthing.org/p/when-you-give-a-claude-a-mouse?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.oneusefulthing.org/p/when-you-give-a-claude-a-mouse?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png" width="114" height="72.18956043956044" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:922,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:114,&quot;bytes&quot;:853090,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div></div></div></a></figure></div><div class="footnote" data-component-name="FootnoteToDOM"><a id="footnote-1" href="#footnote-anchor-1" class="footnote-number" contenteditable="false" target="_self">1</a><div class="footnote-content"><p>Anthropic sent me four prompting hints, which are worth sharing: <br>‚Äù1. Try to limit the usage to simple well specified tasks with explicit instructions about the steps that the model needs to take.</p><p>2.The model sometimes assumes outcomes of actions without explicitly checking for them. To prevent that you can prompt it with ‚ÄúAfter each step take a screenshot and carefully evaluate if the right outcome was present. Explicitly show your thinking: "I have evaluated step X‚Ä¶". If not correct, try again. Only when you confirm the step was executed correctly move on to the next one.‚Äù</p><p>3.Some UI elements (like dropdowns) might be tricky for the model to manipulate using mouse movements. If you experience this try prompting the model to use keyboard shortcuts.</p><p>4.For repeatable tasks or UI interactions, include example screenshots and tool calls showing the model succeeding as part of your prompt prefix.‚Äù</p></div></div></body></html>	The article discusses the capabilities and limitations of AI agents, using the example of an AI system called Claude that was tested on a clicker game. The AI demonstrated strategic thinking and persistence, but also made mistakes and struggled.	2024-10-22 18:17:19	2024-10-26 13:32:48.445	2024-10-26 14:01:31.563	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7e8326f-c834-46f9-971c-83a0ed594041_1536x973.png	Ethan Mollick	when-you-give-a-claude-a-mouse
206	https://timdenning.substack.com/p/i-used-to-be-impressed-by-people-685	I Used to Be Impressed by People Who Had a Lot of Money ‚Äî But Now I‚Äôm Impressed by People Who Have Time to Think Deeply	Being told what to do is the adult daycare 99% of people live in.	<html><head></head><body><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg" width="1024" height="924" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:924,&quot;width&quot;:1024,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:322661,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption"><em>Image Credit‚Äì Midjourney</em></figcaption></figure></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/p/i-used-to-be-impressed-by-people-685?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/p/i-used-to-be-impressed-by-people-685?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p><p>A Rolex watch used to make me weak at the knees.</p><p>I wanted to know how they bought it. I wanted to know every detail of their career and how much money they made. I wanted to know everything about them.</p><p>Now I see this view of the world as stupid ‚Äì it‚Äôs a sign of low IQ.</p><p>Then in the last 5 years I progressed to the view that real wealth is having free time. Free time is nice but if you piss it away it‚Äôs still a stupid goal. In the last 6 months my view on wealth has changed once again.</p><p>Let me break down what the real definition is of wealth.</p><h1>‚ÄúWealth is the product of man‚Äôs capacity to think‚Äù ‚Äì Ayn Rand</h1><p>Ayn was a wild and controversial figure.</p><p>I don‚Äôt like everything she says, but this quote has stuck with me. Most people never spend the time to think deeply. They‚Äôre so busy impressing a boss or trying to fit in that there‚Äôs nothing left.</p><p>Thinking deeply is a luxury. It‚Äôs what wealthy people have secretly done for centuries.</p><p>People like me thought wealthy people just had free time. It‚Äôs only when you study them and are able to hang around them that you realize what they‚Äôre doing is investing time to think deeply.</p><div class="pullquote"><p>Wealth is being a deep thinker, not an overthinker.</p></div><p>If you have no time to think deeply, you‚Äôre experiencing a level of poverty that‚Äôs worse than financial bankruptcy or even homelessness.</p><p>Thinking is how you join the dots in your head to make sense of this crazy world. This process is what forms true wisdom, too. You go from always being a follower and paying attention to external ideas, to having your own ideas.</p><h1>Conformists never unlock true wealth</h1><p>The default path in life is to conform, therefore adopting most of your worldview from somewhere else. This is the path to ruin.</p><p>Dan Koe explains why this is:</p><blockquote><p><em>‚ÄúIn Ego Development Theory, a lower stage of development is the conformist stage.</em></p><p><em>A stage where people can‚Äôt think for themselves. They need to be accepted by the tribe. So their mind sees religion and other ideologies and institutional dogma as law. ‚ÄúBible thumpers‚Äù for more than just the bible.</em></p><p><em>It seems that as new generations gain more of a collective voice, the conformist stage ‚Äì mostly occupied by boomers ‚Äì is slowly starting to fade out from the general population. More people are occupying higher stages of development.‚Äù</em></p></blockquote><p>We all start out as conformists.</p><p>But true wealth happens after you stop conforming and decide it‚Äôs better to be weird and f*ck fitting in. You can spot a conformist a mile away. They‚Äôre glued to their phone screen like it contains the meaning of life and $10M.</p><h1>The idea of true wealth is being reinvented</h1><p>Money can‚Äôt buy you wisdom, and luxury feels like sh*t after you have a few months of it, perhaps, thanks to an inheritance.</p><p>Here‚Äôs what true wealth now looks like:</p><h3>1. A social media newsfeed of 50 people that you curate</h3><p>You must make space for thinking.</p><p>Most people have way too much input. They‚Äôre suffering from information overload. Even worse, when they go on social media they start on the homepage of whatever app they‚Äôre using.</p><p>So they get fed election propaganda and Elon Musk vomit conspiracies.</p><p>Stay the hell away from the default page of any app or website. What I do is curate my online spaces. I log into X most days but I never look at what‚Äôs trending or in the news.</p><p>Instead, I have a small group of high-signal people who I genuinely follow. I read everything they post, and their content is tied to an active goal or obsession I have.</p><p>I‚Äôm not just reading for the sake of reading ‚Äì or to get unearned dopamine.</p><p>If you‚Äôre following more than 50 people you probably need to start again. Once you hone in on the right voices it dials up the ideas you think deeply about offline.</p><p>Less information equals more wisdom.</p><h3>2. Time to sit and stare at a blank wall</h3><p>It‚Äôs rare to do nothing.</p><p>Most of us can‚Äôt bear it. We always have to be doing stuff. But this is what keeps us mentally poor. Blank space allows your mind to rest. Staring at a blank wall is extremely productive. It‚Äôs where I have my best ideas.</p><p>In a world where trading your time for money is 10x less effective than before, your value is determined more by your creativity. Without blank space, you‚Äôre a humanoid robot with nothing valuable to add to society.</p><p>Blank space raises your awareness. That helps you notice your best ideas and join the dots. And, after all, that‚Äôs all creativity is.</p><h3>3. Days and even weeks away from a phone</h3><p>I‚Äôll say it for those in the back of the room:</p><p>The dumbest people I‚Äôve ever met look at phones for hours per day. Since 2020 I‚Äôd be lucky to look at my phone for even 30 minutes in one day.</p><p>Yesterday I went to test drive a Tesla car. The sales guy said ‚ÄúI tried following you up last time but could never get through to you. Is this the best phone number?‚Äù</p><p>Me: ‚ÄúI never answer any phone calls. Most of them are scams or other people‚Äôs obligations forced on me. I never check texts either.‚Äù</p><p>It felt a bit rude to say but it‚Äôs the truth. F*ck phones. They‚Äôve made our lives worse.</p><p>It‚Äôs why my gym is full of phone zombies looking at screens. No one works out anymore. They do one set of bicep curls then look at their phone for the next 30 minutes before doing another one. This isn‚Äôt exercising or building muscle.</p><p>Perhaps we‚Äôll once again face another lack of exercise epidemic as a result.</p><p>The solution is to do a hard reset.</p><p>Find ways to get the hell away from your phone for days or even weeks. By default, having a phone next to you or in your pocket forms anxiety and guarantees you never think deeply.</p><h3>4. A vehicle to express your true creativity</h3><p>Painting, knitting, illustrating, and acting are creative art forms, but for the last 100 years creative people like me have been underpaid.</p><p>It‚Äôs why the term starving artist exists.</p><p>I had a revelation recently (thanks to deep thinking). These more artsy forms of creativity serve a secondary purpose.</p><p>When we paint or draw it helps us unlock our creativity. While right in the thick of creative expression, I often have my biggest breakthroughs.</p><p>Escaping a life problem with an artsy expression of creativity helps my brain figure things out without me observing and, frankly, getting in the way. In a world of AI, we need more human art. Mark my words, a Digital Renaissance is coming.</p><p>Takeaway: waste time on a creative pursuit that has no outcome or goal attached.</p><h3>5. Self-employment instead of a micromanagement job</h3><p>I could never think deeply while I had a job.</p><p>I always had to worry about the next corporate restructure or round of layoffs. Every boss micromanaged me into the ground.</p><p>Even when I went to Japan to have a holiday I couldn‚Äôt escape. My day job constantly plagued my mind with other people‚Äôs problems.</p><p>As soon as you can, make the transition to self-employment ‚Äì even if that means you‚Äôre a consultant or freelancer. It‚Äôs not the label but who tells you what to do that counts.</p><pre><code>Being told what to do is the adult daycare 99% of people live in.</code></pre><p>What‚Äôs wild is the average person doesn‚Äôt even realize they live this way. They think being an adult baby in a daycare is normal, or even noble. Not really, amigo.</p><p>My best thinking happened a month after I quit my banking job forever. It‚Äôs been that way ever since. Suddenly I can think without having to worry what other people think. And I don‚Äôt need outside opinions from anyone to run my life.</p><p>I found all the outside opinions at work a distraction.</p><p>Most of these leaders knew nothing about me, yet they still wanted to give me unsolicited advice and fake-pretend they knew what was best for me, so they could manipulate me into completing their KPIs while they sat in coffee shops ‚Äúnetworking‚Äù and having a good time.</p><h3>6. Blank space to sit and write</h3><p>If you don‚Äôt write you‚Äôre not truly thinking.</p><p>I write to have ideas. Weird how that works.</p><p>Start a daily writing habit. Use it to get to know yourself and make sense of all the inputs. Use it to think, then in the editing process tomorrow just edit out all the mental sludge that accidentally made it in.</p><h3>7. Walk your way into mini-transformations</h3><p>Truly wealthy people walk a lot.</p><p>They use it as a time to think. There‚Äôs something about combining forward movement with thinking that helps you to progress ideas and solve hard problems. Plus it feels good and gets the blood pumping.</p><p>If you don‚Äôt have time to walk for an hour a day, are you truly living? Maybe it‚Äôs a sign.</p><h1>Final Thought</h1><p>You may not be able to do all of these things above.</p><p>But your goal is to make enough money so you can enable this blueprint and experience true wealth. People who think deeply impress the cr*p out of me. I‚Äôm not there yet but I‚Äôm well on my way.</p><p>A life built on deep thinking is true wealth. It‚Äôs the best feeling in the world, and this way of life will help you understand the meaning of life.</p><p>Tell me which of these ideas you loved the most and why in the comments.</p><div><hr></div><p>I send this email weekly. If you would also like to receive it, join the 129,000+ other smart people who absolutely love it today.</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><p>üëâ&nbsp;If you enjoy reading this post, feel free to share it with friends! Or feel free to click the ‚ù§Ô∏è button on this post so more people can discover it on Substack üôè</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/p/i-used-to-be-impressed-by-people-685?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/p/i-used-to-be-impressed-by-people-685?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p></body></html>	Wealth is defined by the ability to think deeply, not by material possessions. True wealth comes from curating information, taking time to think, and expressing creativity.	2024-10-22 10:04:51	2024-10-26 13:32:44.901	2024-10-26 13:32:46.19	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8545fe62-26ac-4973-ad8f-0b5562a15e41_1024x924.jpeg	Tim Denning	i-used-to-be-impressed-by-people-who-had-a-lot-of-money-but-now-im-impressed-by-people-who-have-time-to-think-deeply
208	https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/climate-journalism-done-right	Climate Journalism Done Right	The Washington Post: The Real Reason for Increasing Billion Dollar Disasters	<html><head></head><body><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png" width="362" height="189.95054945054946" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:764,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:362,&quot;bytes&quot;:940332,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div></div></div></a></figure></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><p>Today, The Washington Post has published a lengthy analysis titled, ‚Äú<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/interactive/2024/billion-dollar-disasters-climate-change-economy/?next_url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/interactive/2024/billion-dollar-disasters-climate-change-economy/&amp;tid=usw_paywall">The real reason billion-dollar disasters like Hurricane Helene are growing more common</a>.‚Äù<a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1" target="_self">1</a> The article, by the Post‚Äôs Harry Stevens, is brilliantly done ‚Äî extensively reported, data rich, grounded in a large body of research, with a wide diversity of voices. Watching reactions to the article will be fascinating.<a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-2" href="#footnote-2" target="_self">2</a></p><p>Let‚Äôs take a look at Stevens‚Äô analysis of the NOAA billion dollar disaster (BDD) tabulation and how it has been often mischaracterized in assessments and in policy.</p><p>Stevens opens by explaining why the disaster count matters ‚Äî it is often invoked as a justification for policy:</p><blockquote><p>The <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/access/billions/time-series?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">disaster data</a>, maintained by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, has featured in <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.cbo.gov/publication/59918?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">multiple</a> <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.federalreserve.gov/econres/notes/feds-notes/analyzing-state-resilience-to-climate-change-20230907.html?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">government</a> <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://storymaps.arcgis.com/collections/ad628a4d3e7e4460b089d9fe96b2475d?item=6&amp;itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">reports</a> on global warming. The Biden administration <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2024/07/02/fact-sheet-president-biden-announces-new-actions-to-protect-workers-and-communities-from-extreme-weather/?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">has</a> <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/11/14/fact-sheet-biden-harris-administration-releases-fifth-national-climate-assessment-and-announces-more-than-6-billion-to-strengthen-climate-resilience-across-the-country/?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">referenced</a> <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.whitehouse.gov/ostp/news-updates/2023/11/09/fact-sheet-fifth-national-climate-assessment-details-impacts-of-climate-change-on-regions-across-the-united-states/?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">it</a> <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/09/21/fact-sheet-biden-harris-administration-announces-new-actions-to-reduce-greenhouse-gas-emissions-and-combat-the-climate-crisis/?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">at</a> <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/07/11/fact-sheet-biden-harris-administration-takes-action-to-protect-communities-from-extreme-heat-fueled-by-the-climate-crisis/?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">least</a> <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2021/08/09/fact-sheet-biden-administration-announces-nearly-5-billion-in-resilience-funding-to-help-communities-prepare-for-extreme-weather-and-climate-related-disasters/?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">seven</a> <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2021/03/31/fact-sheet-the-american-jobs-plan/?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">times</a> to help make the case for climate policies. Members of Congress cited it in a <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://www.congress.gov/bill/118th-congress/house-bill/598/text?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">bill</a> to curtail the use of fossil fuels. Last year‚Äôs <a href="https://archive.is/o/dtGSY/https://nca2023.globalchange.gov/chapter/2/?itid=lk_inline_enhanced-template">National Climate Assessment</a>, a<strong> </strong>congressionally mandated report on climate change, showed the disasters on a map under the heading ‚ÄúClimate Change Is Not Just a Problem for Future Generations, It‚Äôs a Problem Today.‚Äù</p><p>But according to disaster experts, former NOAA officials and peer-reviewed scientific studies, the chart says little about climate change. The truth lies elsewhere: Over time, migration to hazard-prone areas has increased, putting more people and property in harm‚Äôs way. Disasters are more expensive because there is more to destroy.</p></blockquote><p>Read that again.</p><p>The Post reports some interesting details on the origins of the BDD dataset:</p><blockquote><p>Neither of them can remember exactly when or whose idea it was, but some time in the early 1990s, Neal Lott and Tom Ross started tracking weather disasters in the United States that caused at least a billion dollars in economic losses. They scoured government reports and phoned insurance companies to compile their list. The job took up a small portion of their time working at what was then called the National Climatic Data Center.</p><p>‚ÄúAt that point, it was not an attempt to do any sort of a scientific study,‚Äù Lott said. ‚ÄúAs far as climate change, that wasn‚Äôt in mind at all.‚Äù</p><p>Each year brought a longer list of disasters, but the two meteorologists did not think the weather had changed. Instead, they noticed there were more people and property in areas prone to natural hazards.</p></blockquote><p>Tom Ross, the former NOAA official, has a great quote:</p><blockquote><p>‚ÄúIt doesn‚Äôt take as much to get to a billion dollars now than it did 20 years ago .If a storm hiccups, it gets a billion dollars‚Äô worth of damage now, whereas 20 years ago, it took a lot more than a hiccup to do it.‚Äù</p></blockquote><p>The NOAA official currently responsible for assembling the BDD tabulation, and who has been in that role for more than a decade, offered a remarkable admission to the Post:</p><blockquote><p>‚ÄúWe‚Äôve never sought to do attribution studies in relation to the extremes listed in the billion-dollar disaster dataset.‚Äù</p></blockquote><p>That means that all of the claims made by NOAA and public officials claiming that the increase in BDD counts has been driven by human-caused changes in the climatology of extreme weather are not grounded in any attribution analysis whatsoever.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png" width="536" height="319.1838671411625" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/df01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:502,&quot;width&quot;:843,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:536,&quot;bytes&quot;:861845,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf01476b-4dc4-4350-93ed-1d0a33be8282_843x502.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption">Disaster normalization OGs</figcaption></figure></div><p>The Post does a nice job situating our research in the broader context of their analysis ‚Äî starting with me and NOAA‚Äôs Chris Landsea in the mid-1990s and later with many more wonderful colleagues. You can read about how our first paper on disaster normalization began on a basketball court.</p><p>For the first time I can remember, a time series of mainland U.S. hurricane landfalls has been published by the major media as part of the Post‚Äôs explanation of our hurricane ‚Äúnormalization‚Äù research. The four panels below are a nice way to show trends underlying increasing disaster losses ‚Äî I‚Äôm going to use this in future talks.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png" width="891" height="683" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:683,&quot;width&quot;:891,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:63644,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F67492d02-c908-472e-8065-ccc5da1d099a_891x683.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><p>The hurricane landfall data shown above follows from our 2018 paper (which covered 1900-2017), and I‚Äôve just updated hurricane and major hurricane landfall trends (through today) in the figure below.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png" width="366" height="389.2179930795848" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:922,&quot;width&quot;:867,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:366,&quot;bytes&quot;:156415,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7052aa35-9290-4af0-88ff-8860c04bfdc9_867x922.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption">Updated to 24 October 2024 from <a href="https://journals.ametsoc.org/view/journals/bams/99/7/bams-d-17-0184.1.xml">Klotzbach et al. 2018</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>The post quotes Laurens Bouwer ‚Äî one of the world‚Äôs experts on disasters and climate change as well as a long-time IPCC contributor ‚Äî on the current scientific consensus:</p><blockquote><p>Yet the consensus among disaster researchers is that the rise in billion-dollar disasters, while alarming, is not so much an indicator of climate change as a reflection of societal growth and risky development.</p><p>‚ÄúA lot of the things we see in the disaster losses are obscured because there‚Äôs an overwhelming signal of more people in risky places, growing populations worldwide, more infrastructure, more assets, higher values,‚Äù said [Laurens] Bouwer, the five-time IPCC lead author. ‚ÄúThis is the main signal. And that‚Äôs where the science is at the moment.‚Äù</p></blockquote><p>The Post also quotes me on scientific integrity, which I think is the larger story here:</p><blockquote><p>‚ÄúI always want to emphasize climate change is real. It‚Äôs serious,‚Äù Pielke said. ‚ÄúBut that doesn‚Äôt mean anything goes when it comes to science.‚Äù</p></blockquote><p>The article is richly reported and includes much more than I‚Äôve discussed here.<a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-3" href="#footnote-3" target="_self">3</a> Before I send you to read the whole thing, I want to highlight some remarkable statements and admissions from NOAA, the Biden Administration, and U.S. National Climate Assessment (NCA) contributors:</p><ul><li><p>In a statement to the Post, the White House doubles down on attribution: ‚ÄúAmericans are already feeling the impacts of hurricanes, wildfires, floods, and drought. The science is clear: climate change is the existential threat of our time.‚Äù</p></li><li><p>NOAA also doubles down: ‚ÄúA lot of these extremes are really ramped up. If you want to act like nothing‚Äôs happening or it‚Äôs minimal, that‚Äôs just not the case . . .‚Äù</p></li><li><p>A NCA lead author (who happens to work for a climate activist organization) suggested that we should just assume attribution, no science needed: ‚ÄúI think then the burden might be to demonstrate that detected climate influence therefore has no effect whatsoever on the associated costs.‚Äù</p></li><li><p>Another NCA author stated that the BDD tabulation served promotional purposes, ‚Äúto clearly communicate that climate change is a present-day problem here in the United States with significant impacts. We wanted to counter the common perception that climate change is a problem for the future and for someone else.‚Äù</p></li><li><p>Yet another NCA author explained that researchers felt pressure (from whom?) to connect climate changes to costs experienced today: ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs been a lot of pressure on climate scientists to tell the story better.‚Äù</p></li></ul><p>There is much, much more in the analysis and I encourage you to <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/interactive/2024/billion-dollar-disasters-climate-change-economy/?next_url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/interactive/2024/billion-dollar-disasters-climate-change-economy/&amp;tid=usw_paywall">read the whole thing.</a> This is climate reporting done right. Bravo Wash Post!</p><p>PS. I notice as I am writing this that Andy Revkin at SustainWhat is <a href="https://revkin.substack.com/p/live-10-am-et-join-a-fresh-look-at">hosting a discission</a> with Harry Stevens on the article. which will be available at Andy‚Äôs Substack and on YouTube. </p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/climate-journalism-done-right/comments&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Leave a comment&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/climate-journalism-done-right/comments"><span>Leave a comment</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><div class="footnote" data-component-name="FootnoteToDOM"><a id="footnote-1" href="#footnote-anchor-1" class="footnote-number" contenteditable="false" target="_self">1</a><div class="footnote-content"><p>You can also find the article at this <a href="https://archive.is/dtGSY">archived link</a>.</p></div></div><div class="footnote" data-component-name="FootnoteToDOM"><a id="footnote-2" href="#footnote-anchor-2" class="footnote-number" contenteditable="false" target="_self">2</a><div class="footnote-content"><p>Some may recall that it was exactly this topic that led to the mobbing of Nate Silver and the witch hunt that forced me out of 538 back in 2014. Let‚Äôs see what has changed 10 years on.</p></div></div><div class="footnote" data-component-name="FootnoteToDOM"><a id="footnote-3" href="#footnote-anchor-3" class="footnote-number" contenteditable="false" target="_self">3</a><div class="footnote-content"><p>My one criticism of the article is that the Post felt it necessary to politicize my work by associating it with Republicans and explaining who I‚Äôll be voting for this election (Harris, duh). No other researcher in the article is treated the same way. The fact that my (and colleagues) research is found convincing by some Republicans (but not the Maga ones) should be welcomed ‚Äî Many climate researchers spend a lot of time denigrating Republicans, how‚Äôs that been working out for building trust in climate science?</p></div></div></body></html>	The Washington Post article analyzes the NOAA billion-dollar disaster dataset, which has been used to justify climate policies.	2024-10-24 14:54:43	2024-10-26 13:32:51.333	2024-10-26 14:01:31.563	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b6c864b-36e4-4988-b0cc-0753b722f5c9_2916x1531.png	Roger Pielke Jr.	climate-journalism-done-right
205	https://timdenning.substack.com/p/set-a-bar-so-high-average-people	Set a Bar so High Average People Think You're a Psychopath	‚ÄúYour potential is determined by how much uncertainty you're willing to embrace‚Äù	<html><head></head><body><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg" width="742" height="437" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:437,&quot;width&quot;:742,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:102514,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption"><em>Image Credit: Midjourney</em></figcaption></figure></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/p/set-a-bar-so-high-average-people?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/p/set-a-bar-so-high-average-people?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p><p>He sat in the middle of the road in a puddle of vomit.</p><p>Luckily, cars dodged his lifeless body. We were outside of a strip club. When he finally got up he wanted more vodka. We were cooked. The walls started to look like they were caving in. Any advances he made toward the opposite s*x were rejected.</p><p>I tried to stay married to his average way of life. He was my best friend. During some years he was my only friend.</p><p>On our final night together we went to his friend‚Äôs house. I was assured of a good time. We watched some American Idol. Nothing too serious. Then the alcohol came out. Then the coke came out. 2 hours later a lady friend knocked on the door.</p><p>She was a stripper.</p><p>Soon she was naked practicing her dance routine on all the boys. I felt disgusting. The next day the owner of the house‚Äôs Audi out front was gone. A drug dealer stole it for not paying debts. His mother paid for the car. She was devastated.</p><p>The slippery slope of being average can lead to dark f*cking places.</p><p>From that day on I divorced my best friend. I raised the bar so high in my life that I had no friends for more than 2 years. I started again.</p><p>Former friends thought I was a psychopath. Sometimes they still send me DJ videos on Facebook. They don‚Äôt understand that I‚Äôm not a DJ anymore, and will never go to a nightclub again or ever drink alcohol.</p><p>If you want to be successful, it‚Äôs good for average people to call you a psychopath.</p><div class="pullquote"><p>"You are under no obligation to be the same person you were 5 minutes ago" ‚Äì Alan Watts</p></div><h1>‚ÄúYour potential is determined by how much uncertainty you're willing to embrace‚Äù</h1><p>(Dan Koe)</p><p>Why don‚Äôt people raise their standards?</p><p>Because it‚Äôs full of uncertainty. It‚Äôs easier and more comfortable to fit in and get told what to do. Being average is the default path.</p><p>You don‚Äôt have to think twice. No one is gonna protest because of your decision. In fact, being average carries no decision. It‚Äôs a life of indecision, maybes, somedays, and unknown regrets.</p><p>We so-called psychopaths take risks.</p><p>Not blind risks. Not stupid decisions. But calculated and data-backed risks that seem crazy to the outside world. Living like this requires you to have a good relationship with uncertainty.</p><p>You‚Äôre fine not to know the outcome. You get used to entropy running your emotions. You crave a bit of luck and scenarios you could never have predicted.</p><p>Insisting on having a plan and knowing the outcome upfront is the fastest way to the land of ruin.</p><div class="pullquote"><p>‚ÄúYou have one life. Don‚Äôt settle for mediocrity.‚Äù ‚Äì Naval Ravikant</p></div><h1>Being above average becomes a weird religion</h1><blockquote><p>‚ÄúYou must understand the following: In order to master a field, you must love the subject and feel a profound connection to it. <strong>Your interest must transcend the field itself and border on the religious‚Äù</strong> ‚Äì Robert Greene</p></blockquote><p>The best things in life are a religion.</p><p>I bought a Tesla last week because I needed a new car. People have already called me an Elon Musk groupie. I only bought the car because it‚Äôs the safest one on the planet to transport my 1 year old daughter.</p><p>Soon as I started looking at some accessories, I found out Tesla is a religion. When you buy this car you worship software and minimalism. More bizarrely, you worship the future of the planet. One run by robots and AI. You‚Äôre optimistic by nature.</p><p>Being above average is a religion too.</p><p>Whatever your obsession is you have to practice it like a form of religion. You‚Äôll likely be in a cult of others who have the same obsession.</p><p>A religion is spiritual. It transcends the act of doing. There‚Äôs a deeper why. A meaning behind it. The religion is connected to the universe.</p><p>What you do creates tiny ripples that may create tidal waves later in history.</p><p>Some people hate religion. They think worshipping a god is stupid. Not me. I‚Äôm not part of any church, but I do see the benefits of how religion works.</p><p>No one can convince a religious person that another way of living exists or there is no god. When you apply that mindset to an obsession it‚Äôs a powerful cocktail. Every time I sit down to write I have a religious experience.</p><p>It feels like I‚Äôm channeling a level of inspiration that can wake people up, and help them escape the hell of the rat race.</p><p>Perhaps I‚Äôm delusional. Or insane.</p><h1>Single-minded selfishness that‚Äôll light your ass on fire and make people cheer</h1><p>Acts of obsession start out as selfish.</p><p>Over time, though, they turn into acts of selflessness. But if you never use selfishness to cross the threshold of effort needed to gain traction, nothing will ever happen.</p><p>Naval Ravikant says:</p><pre><code>‚ÄúReplace all desires with a single desire.‚Äù</code></pre><p>This is what obsession is. There‚Äôs no to-do list. No having multiple goals. No multi-interests. The entire approach is psychopathic. Like a murderer who decides to kill the president and stops at nothing until the job is done. They think about and do nothing else. They may even get shot themselves in the process.</p><p>Having more than one thing is how you become nothing. Your job is to keep the main thing the main thing so you never do anything else.</p><h1>‚ÄúBe so good they call you fake‚Äù</h1><p>(Max Baudasch)</p><p>On the path to being a psychopath people have called me all sorts of things. They love to say I‚Äôm fake or that this Substack is written by AI.</p><p>Average people set the bar low so when they get rejected or criticized, they curl up into a ball and eat Oreos.&nbsp;&nbsp;A psychopath following their obsession is different.</p><p>They expect to be called fake. They hope they attract critics.</p><p>When you put ideas out into the world some people will disagree. That‚Äôs mother nature at work. What‚Äôs dangerous is when you DON‚ÄôT put ideas into the world. That means you‚Äôre a slave to other people‚Äôs ideas. You‚Äôre confirming like a good little sheep.</p><p>When you conform no one will disagree. But also, no one will give you opportunities. You‚Äôll have to apply for them, and even then, it‚Äôll be like playing the lottery.</p><p>When I was a tech recruiter I noticed high performers came to job interviews with one or two big ideas. They were deep thinkers. They offered something hiring managers couldn‚Äôt resist.</p><p>Let critics call you fake because it‚Äôs better than being normal.</p><h1>Adopt solitary habits</h1><p>Solitary confinement in prison is often described as a blessing by inmates.</p><p>Prisoners get thrown in the hole and come out different people. They have a lot of time to think. They realize no one cares if they win or lose. It‚Äôs rock bottom.</p><p>Only at rock bottom do you find real answers to the big problems in your life.</p><p>I‚Äôve never cried harder than when I got my social media job taken away. It hurt worse than seeing my best friend get stabbed (almost to death) outside a shopping center. Don‚Äôt worry, I got beaten to a pulp with a baseball bat.</p><p>Ash Jogalekar says we should have solitary habits:</p><blockquote><p>Reading is a solitary hobby.<br>Long-distance running is a solitary hobby.<br>Science - to some extent - is a solitary hobby.</p><p>Solitary hobbies provide you with a retreat from personal tragedies and the tragedies of the world.</p></blockquote><p>The best solitary habit I‚Äôve found is writing. It‚Äôs a place where I can think and have ideas while doing it.</p><p>We‚Äôre taught to always be around other people. But too much socializing is often a distraction and a form of procrastination.</p><ul><li><p>Insecure people need company all the time.</p></li><li><p>Successful people are confident to go it alone.</p></li></ul><p>Raise your standards and accept more alone time. That‚Äôs where your obsession is built and psychopath mode is turned on.</p><h1>One day you‚Äôll laugh at your old life</h1><p>My friend Michael Thompson has two wild kids.</p><p>He used to be a banker like me. Now he‚Äôs a storyteller and shows others how to master the craft. Recently he moved house. His kids found his box of ties from work. They tied the ties together and made a skipping rope out of them.</p><p>Each day he looks out the kitchen window and sees them skipping over his ties. It‚Äôs a constant reminder of his old life that he now laughs at.</p><p>It‚Äôs the same in my life. My daughter found my ties hanging in the wardrobe. They‚Äôre full of dust and haven‚Äôt been worn for years. Yesterday I caught her wiping her nose on my bright pink tie. It made me smile.</p><p>I don‚Äôt miss my old life of asking for permission and being told what to do. Or sitting down in an office chair googling random stuff online to burn time until it‚Äôs home time.</p><h1>How to have the mindset of an obsessed psychopath</h1><ul><li><p>Be willing to go broke. Because you can always make the money back again. Protecting the little you have is how you never become wealthy.</p></li><li><p>Raise your standards for the people you let into your life. No losers. No lovers of politics. No one who watches the news daily.</p></li><li><p>Piss on the idea of ‚Äúbalance‚Äù and embrace imbalance. Love the chaos. Thrive in it. Choose it.</p></li><li><p>Choose one goal and work on it for 10 years while doing 10,000 iterations.</p></li><li><p>Work on an obsession that 99% of people don‚Äôt understand.</p></li><li><p>Spend more time alone while you build your dream.</p></li><li><p>Face uncertainty with a smile.</p></li><li><p>Never choose ‚Äúrealistic‚Äù ever again.</p></li><li><p>Work for 4 hours a day in a flow state.</p></li><li><p>Turn your obsession into financial wealth.</p></li><li><p>Expect to be overwhelmed and celebrate it.</p></li><li><p>Progress from a job to your own business.</p></li><li><p>Dare to work after hours and on weekends.</p></li><li><p>Enjoy being the dumbest person in the room.</p></li><li><p>Stop asking for permission and just do it.</p></li><li><p>Refuse to ever go back to university.</p></li><li><p>Come up with delusional ideas.</p></li><li><p>Turn anger into inspiration.</p></li><li><p>Set goals that seem crazy.</p></li><li><p>Prove people wrong.</p></li></ul><p>Obsession looks like madness to the untrained mind. Good. Ambition isn‚Äôt a mental disorder. Being mediocre is.</p><p>Tell me which of these ideas you loved the most and why in the comments.</p><div><hr></div><p>P.S. When you‚Äôre ready to join others who set insanely high bars, book your seat to <em>The Fearless Writer Challenge</em>.&nbsp;</p><p>Only catch ‚Äî we start very soon.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://fearless.badasseryacademy.com/">You can grab your seat on this page today</a>.</p></body></html>	The article discusses the benefits of raising one's standards and embracing uncertainty to achieve success, even if it means being labeled a "psychopath" by average people.	2024-10-24 10:05:02	2024-10-26 13:32:43.317	2024-10-26 14:01:31.563	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc71c8bca-b4aa-4de3-93be-3465695ca21c_742x437.jpeg	Tim Denning	set-a-bar-so-high-average-people-think-youre-a-psychopath
209	https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/we-found-an-excel-file-online	We Found an Excel File Online	The continuing adventures of a fake climate dataset	<html><head></head><body><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png" width="411" height="411.6930860033727" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:594,&quot;width&quot;:593,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:411,&quot;bytes&quot;:1069663,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption">Boo! Zombie hurricane data.</figcaption></figure></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><div class="pullquote"><p>‚ÄúData are the foundation on which scientific, engineering, and medical knowledge is built.‚Äù  <a href="https://nap.nationalacademies.org/catalog/12615/ensuring-the-integrity-accessibility-and-stewardship-of-research-data-in-the-digital-age">National Academy of Sciences 2009</a>.</p></div><p>A <a href="https://journals.ametsoc.org/view/journals/apme/aop/JAMC-D-24-0047.1/JAMC-D-24-0047.1.xml">new paper</a> is just out claiming that climate change is increasing the damage associated with U.S. hurricanes:</p><blockquote><p>‚ÄúUS hurricane damage, normalized for changes of inflation, population, and wealth, increases approximately 1% per year. For 1900‚Äì2022, 1% per year is equivalent to a factor of &gt;3 increase, substantially but not entirely, attributable to climate change.‚Äù</p></blockquote><p>As they say ‚Äî <a href="https://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=big%20if%20true">Big if true</a>.</p><p>Alas, it is not true. Stop me if you‚Äôve heard this before ‚Äî some researchers found a fake Excel ‚Äúdataset‚Äù online and decided to use it in a peer reviewed paper, favoring the fake dataset over data in the peer reviewed literature of known provenance and subject to decades of scrutiny. </p><p>The authors of the new paper assert of their work with the fake dataset:</p><blockquote><p>‚ÄúThese results contradict the previously published work‚Äù</p></blockquote><p>Indeed.</p><div class="pullquote"><p>‚ÄúResearchers have a fundamental obligation to their colleagues, to the public, and to themselves to ensure the integrity of research data.‚Äù <a href="https://nap.nationalacademies.org/catalog/12615/ensuring-the-integrity-accessibility-and-stewardship-of-research-data-in-the-digital-age">National Academy of Sciences 2009.</a></p></div><p>I have described <a href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/apples-oranges-and-normalized-hurricane">in detail and with receipts</a> the origins of the fake dataset of U.S. hurricane losses. I know all about it because I helped to set up the original not-fake version of the dataset in the late 2000s with one of my former students. In partnership with an insurance company, ICAT, we thought it would be useful to create an online tool to show historical, normalized U.S. hurricane losses based on our <a href="https://ascelibrary.org/doi/abs/10.1061/(ASCE)1527-6988(2008)9:1(29)">peer-reviewed research</a>. So we created the ICAT Damage Estimator, shown with a fuzzy old screenshot below.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png" width="500" height="342.5" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:274,&quot;width&quot;:400,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:500,&quot;bytes&quot;:264166,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F209a7d24-ec19-4ece-bac3-bb72e1640300_400x274.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption">The ICAT Damage Estimator circa <a href="https://rogerpielkejr.blogspot.com/2011/08/hurricane-irene-damage-analogues.html">2011</a>.</figcaption></figure></div><p>It was a very cool tool. It took data from <a href="https://ascelibrary.org/doi/abs/10.1061/(ASCE)1527-6988(2008)9:1(29)">Pielke et al. 2008</a> ‚Äî unaltered ‚Äî and displayed historical hurricanes and their normalized damage in relation to currently active storms in the Atlantic. The ICAT Damage Estimator was at the time (circa 2011) a <a href="https://ams.confex.com/ams/91Annual/webprogram/Paper186426.html">solid scientific tool</a> and appropriately got a lot of attention. </p><p>Time moved along ‚Äî ICAT was sold, my students moved on to their careers, and I lost touch with whomever was overseeing the Damage Estimator, which was eventually and appropriately scuttled. Over these years however the data underlying the tool was modified, supplemented, and extended in ways that diverged from our or anyone‚Äôs peer-reviewed research. By the time the Damage Estimator was taken offline (~2017) the ‚Äúdataset‚Äù had morphed into something decidedly unscientific.</p><p>Most notably, at some point, data in the tool on hurricane losses post-1980 was <a href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/apples-oranges-and-normalized-hurricane">replaced with the tabulation from the NOAA Billion Dollar loss dataset</a>. Uh-oh.</p><p>The splicing of two very different datasets together is a recipe for problems. The <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s44304-024-00011-0">NOAA Billion Dollar dataset</a> takes a maximalist approach to loss estimation ‚Äî which might be fine for its purposes ‚Äî but official hurricane loss data from 1900-1979 was not tabulated using such a maximal approach, meaning that the spliced dataset has <a href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/apples-oranges-and-normalized-hurricane">80 years of apples followed by &gt;40 years of oranges</a>.</p><p>To take just one obvious and undeniable example ‚Äî The post-1980 maximalist data includes costs incurred by the National Flood Insurance Program (NFIP) for flooding associated with hurricanes. Such costs can run into many tens of billions of dollars for the most damaging hurricanes. These are real costs.</p><p>However, the NFIP was only created in 1968 and systematically expanded in its implementation over the past half century. That means that there were no NFIP costs prior to 1968 ‚Äî So, for instance, comparing a hurricane‚Äôs damage in 1938 with one in 2008 would be problematic if the latter includes NFIP losses and the former did not. Such details are what makes normalization a bit tricky and is among the many methodological issues we have often <a href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/17477891.2012.738642">dealt with in our research</a>.</p><p>The problems with the ‚ÄúICAT Dataset‚Äù run much deeper than just the inclusion of flood insurance. Consider that from 1900 to 2017 there are <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41893-018-0165-2">197 official loss estimates</a> for hurricanes. The ‚ÄúICAT Dataset‚Äù has 247 loss estimates over the same time period, which means that 50 loss estimates were at some point added to our time series ‚Äî No one knows where those estimates came from or how they were created.</p><p>To illustrate the problems with dataset splicing, I downloaded <a href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/apples-oranges-and-normalized-hurricane">a version of the ‚ÄúICAT Dataset‚Äù</a> and simply tallied its base damage estimates (i.e., estimates prior to normalization or inflation adjustments) over different time periods. I then compared these tallies to the <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41893-018-0165-2">official loss estimates</a> of the National Hurricane Center for the same time periods. Here are the ratios of total ICAT to NHC base damage estimates:</p><ul><li><p>1900 to 1979: 112%</p></li><li><p>1980 to 2017: 141%</p></li></ul><p>The ICAT tallies are slightly larger than those of the NHC for the period 1900 to 1979 because of the inclusion of many of the 50 extra storms, most <a href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/apples-oranges-and-normalized-hurricane">individual storm estimates are however identical over this period</a>. From 1980 to 2017 the ICAT total is much larger than the official NHC estimates because the <a href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/apples-oranges-and-normalized-hurricane">methods for aggregating losses is different</a> across the splice.</p><p>The data discontinuity resulting from splicing together two different datasets fully explains the resulting trend ‚Äî Not climate change.</p><p>Despite its dodgy history, the fake ‚ÄúICAT dataset‚Äù might be preferred by some researchers because it gives results that are contrary to the broader peer-reviewed literature. </p><p>We should question such claims of attribution of damages to a changing climate simply because climate data on hurricanes does not support claims of attribution. Don‚Äôt take it from me ‚Äî here is what <a href="https://www.gfdl.noaa.gov/global-warming-and-hurricanes/">NOAA GFDL explained earlier this month</a>, while recognizing the reality of human-caused climate change:</p><blockquote><p>. . . it is premature to conclude with high confidence that human-caused increases in greenhouse gases have caused a change in past Atlantic basin hurricane activity that is outside the range of natural variability . . .</p></blockquote><p>Apparently there is such a felt need to connect hurricanes (and their damage) to climate change that researchers will even use a fake ‚Äúdataset‚Äù they found online back in 2017, peer reviewers will not question it, and a respected scientific journal will publish it. </p><p>Over the weekend I emailed the lead author of the new paper and the journal editor to share the unwelcome news that they have written and published an analysis using a fatally flawed dataset. The lead author responded and he was not happy. He invited a ‚Äúspirited discussion.‚Äù Good, that is in the wheelhouse of THB. This post kicks of what I hope is such a discussion, out in public where it belongs.</p><p>To that end, I am happy to invite the <a href="https://journals.ametsoc.org/view/journals/apme/aop/JAMC-D-24-0047.1/JAMC-D-24-0047.1.xml">authors of the new paper</a> to write up a defense of the ‚ÄúICAT Database,‚Äù to explain its provenance, and why it should be preferred over the official records and methods of the dataset collected by the U.S. National Hurricane Center, subject to peer-review in many papers over the past 25+ years.</p><p>More generally, the climate science community needs to stop publishing studies that use the fake ‚ÄúICAT Dataset‚Äù which has been the basis for <a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C6&amp;q=%22icat+dataset%22+hurricane&amp;btnG=">dozens of peer-reviewed papers</a>. However, zombie data is proving difficult to kill off.</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/we-found-an-excel-file-online/comments&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Leave a comment&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/we-found-an-excel-file-online/comments"><span>Leave a comment</span></a></p><p>Official, peer reviewed hurricane loss data and a normalization using that data can be found at the link below.</p><p>Weinkle, J., Landsea, C., Collins, D., Musulin, R., Crompton, R. P., Klotzbach, P. J., &amp; Pielke Jr, R. (2018). <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41893-018-0165-2">Normalized hurricane damage in the continental United States 1900‚Äì2017</a>. <em>Nature sustainability</em>, <em>1</em>(12), 808-813.</p><div class="file-embed-wrapper" data-component-name="FileToDOM"><div class="file-embed-container-reader"><div class="file-embed-container-top"><img class="file-embed-thumbnail-default" src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack.com%2Fimg%2Fattachment_icon.svg"><div class="file-embed-details"><div class="file-embed-details-h1">Weinkle Et Al 2018 41893 2018 165 Moesm2 Esm</div><div class="file-embed-details-h2">69.1KB ‚àô XLSX file</div></div><a class="file-embed-button wide" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/api/v1/file/a6506e99-b5a7-4165-94ad-cf34ce35dc22.xlsx"><span class="file-embed-button-text">Download</span></a></div><a class="file-embed-button narrow" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/api/v1/file/a6506e99-b5a7-4165-94ad-cf34ce35dc22.xlsx"><span class="file-embed-button-text">Download</span></a></div></div><p><em>THB exists because of the support of readers like you. You can still get 30% off a paid subscription ‚Äî forever, ‚Äî by becoming a THB paid subscriber, but just for a few more days! </em></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?coupon=43822229&amp;utm_content=150492185&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Get 30% off forever&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?coupon=43822229&amp;utm_content=150492185"><span>Get 30% off forever</span></a></p></body></html>	Researchers used a fake dataset to claim climate change is increasing hurricane damage in the U.S., contradicting peer-reviewed literature. The dataset has a dubious history and splices different data sources, leading to flawed conclusions.	2024-10-21 13:03:18	2024-10-26 13:32:53.058	2024-10-26 14:01:31.563	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe958996-cbfc-474c-817d-feadbdc52261_593x594.png	Roger Pielke Jr.	we-found-an-excel-file-online
213	https://babyvc.substack.com/p/early-stage-funds-surge-wildfire	Early-Stage Funds Surge, Wildfire Detection from Space, Real-time AI Audio Translations, and much more...	What's Up Tech? #196	<html><head></head><body><p>Welcome to our <strong>196th </strong>newsletter, written with üñ§ by <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/annika-bautista-453106168/">Annika Bautista</a> and <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/sarah-luna-mongin/">Sarah Luna Mongin</a></p><pre><code>üîç Topics we'll cover this week</code></pre><ul><li><p><strong>Fundraising &amp; general news from the week</strong>: huge incoming funds for early-stage startups, and AI changing the game for translations and wildfire protection</p></li><li><p><strong>Up-and-coming ventures to watch: </strong>two French Deep Tech startups to discover </p></li><li><p><strong>Internships &amp; Job</strong> <strong>offers</strong> of the week </p></li></ul><p>Enjoy the read! üíõ</p><pre><code><code>ü§ë Fundraisings of the week</code></code></pre><h3>üöÄ <strong>20VC raises its largest fund-to-date, $400 million for early-stage startups</strong></h3><p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/harrystebbings/">Harry Stebbings</a> says he‚Äôs ready to <strong>‚Äúmake Europe great again.‚Äù </strong>Stebbings debuted  <a href="https://www.thetwentyminutevc.com/">20VC</a> in 2020 with an <strong>$8.3 million fund</strong> after dropping out of law school. Since then, it has become one of the most popular venture capital firms in Europe on the back of building a successful media platform and landing interviews with the likes of Sam Altman and Scooter Braun. The firm also has <a href="https://techcrunch.com/2024/10/15/20vc-closes-new-400m-fund-to-make-europe-great-again-says-harry-stebbings/">autonomous sub-funds</a>, led by operators and founders, which invest $5 million in pre-seed and seed companies. üå±</p><p>The new raise will be split across two geographies (Europe and the U.S.) and two funds: <strong>$125 million in seed investments</strong> and <strong>$275 million in Series A</strong>. Some notable previous investments from 20VC are <a href="https://poolside.ai/">poolside</a>, <a href="https://www.11x.ai/">11x</a>, and <a href="https://tripledotstudios.com/">Tripledot</a>.</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://sifted.eu/articles/harry-stebbings-third-fund-400-news">Podcaster-turned-VC Harry Stebbings Raises $400 million for Third Fund</a></p></blockquote><div><hr></div><h3>üôå <strong>node.vc raises ‚Ç¨71 million to back Nordic entrepreneurs </strong></h3><p><a href="http://node.vc/">node.vc</a> has closed its first fund, fueling tech startups within the Nordic ecosystem. They are backed by notable investors, including <a href="https://www.saminvest.se/en/">Saminvest</a>, Sweden‚Äôs fund-of-funds, and <a href="https://www.nordea.com/en">Nordea</a>, one of the largest banks in the Nordics. The firm focuses on a <strong>founder-first approach</strong>, aiming to be a ‚Äúnode‚Äù that connects young startup founders with seasoned and successful entrepreneurs. So far, they have invested in three startups: <a href="https://lemonado.io/">Lemonado</a> and <a href="https://starhive.com/">Starhive</a> (no-code AI platforms), and <a href="https://www.rorointeractive.com/">Roro</a> (a gaming studio). ü§ñ</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://tech.eu/2024/10/16/node-vc-closes-71m-fund-for-nordic-entrepreneurs/">node.vc Closes ‚Ç¨71 million Fund for Nordic Entrepreneurs</a></p></blockquote><div><hr></div><h3>üî• OroraTech secures ‚Ç¨25 million to expand AI-powered wildfire detection and global prevention (üá©üá™)</h3><p>SpaceTech company <a href="https://ororatech.com/">OroraTech</a>, which utilizes thermal satellites and AI to predict and prevent wildfires, has secured <strong>‚Ç¨25 million in Series B funding</strong>. The investment will accelerate OroraTech's <strong>global expansion</strong>, particularly in North America and the Asia Pacific, and enhance its AI-driven wildfire detection platform and orbital thermal sensor network.</p><p>With existing investors recommitting capital and a recent <a href="https://ororatech.com/ororatech-raises-25-million-in-series-b-funding-round-for-predictive-ai-global-expansion/">‚Ç¨20 million contract</a> with the <a href="https://www.esa.int/">European Space Agency</a>, OroraTech is positioned as a key player in wildfire management. ‚òÑÔ∏è</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://tech.eu/2024/10/16/satellite-wildfire-detector-ororatech-raises-eur25m-series-b-round/">Satellite Wildfire Detector OroraTech Raises ‚Ç¨25 million Series B</a></p></blockquote><div><hr></div><h3>üîä <strong>Gladia advances real-time audio translations with new Series A fundraise of ‚Ç¨16 million (üá´üá∑)</strong></h3><p>True real-time audio translations are closer than you may think. üëÄ</p><p><a href="https://www.gladia.io/">Gladia</a>, known for developing a cutting-edge speech-to-text API, has now covered over 100 languages, and reached over 600 enterprise customers and 70,000 users worldwide. Along with its new Series A round led by <a href="https://www.xange.vc/">XAnge</a>, Gladia has announced its latest product, Gladia Real-time, which <strong>can process audio data under <a href="https://www.gladia.io/blog/road-to-real-time-audio-ai-series-a">300 miliseconds</a>.</strong> Users can even get smart insights, such as caller sentiment, a summary of key information, and a transcript nearly instantaneously.</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://www.gladia.io/blog/road-to-real-time-audio-ai-series-a">Our Road to Real-Time Audio AI ‚Äì with $16 million in Series A Funding</a></p></blockquote><div><hr></div><h3>üåä CorPower Ocean secures ‚Ç¨32 million to accelerate wave energy commercialisation (<strong>üá∏üá™</strong>)</h3><p><a href="https://corpowerocean.com/">CorPower Ocean</a>, a Swedish wave energy pioneer, has raised <strong>‚Ç¨32 million in a Series B1 funding</strong> round to support the commercial deployment of its innovative wave energy technology. </p><p>The startup has created a wave energy device capable of withstanding severe ocean storms while efficiently <strong>generating power</strong>. The CEO, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/patrik-m%C3%B6ller-669114/">Patrik M√∂ller</a>, highlighted the significance of these trials, which proved the device‚Äôs resilience and energy efficiency. </p><p>Investors emphasized the company‚Äôs potential to tap into <strong>ocean energy markets</strong> across Europe, the US and Japan. üìà</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://www.eu-startups.com/2024/10/stockholm-based-corpower-ocean-secures-e32-million-to-drive-commercialisation-of-wave-energy/">Stockholm-based CorPower Ocean Secures ‚Ç¨32 million to Drive Commercialization of Wave Energy</a></p></blockquote><div><hr></div><h3>üõ° <strong>Sto√Øk protects SME‚Äôs from cyber-attacks with fresh funding of ‚Ç¨25 million (üá´üá∑)</strong></h3><p>Cyber insurance startup <a href="https://www.stoik.com/en-us">Sto√Øk</a> has just raised <strong>‚Ç¨25 million in Series B funding</strong>, led by <a href="https://alven.co/">Alven</a> and with participation from <a href="https://a16z.com/">Andreessen Horowitz</a>. The company is set to expand to Southern Europe, Benelux, and the Nordics, while its focus remains on protecting SMEs. <a href="https://www.maddyness.com/2024/10/15/stoik-leve-25-millions-deuros-pour-assurer-les-entreprises-europeennes-contre-les-cyber-attaques/">According to CEO Jules Veyrat</a>, only 5-10% of SME‚Äôs in Europe have adequate coverage for large-scale cyber-attacks. </p><p>As the first insurer in Europe specializing in cyber risk for small and medium-sized businesses, Sto√Øk is addressing the growing need for affordable and specialized digital security solutions. üëÆ</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://techcrunch.com/2024/10/14/european-cyber-insurance-startup-stoik-secures-27-million/">European Cyber Insurance Startup Sto√Øk Secures $27 million</a></p></blockquote><pre><code><code>üî• Up-and-coming startups to watch</code></code></pre><h3>üõ∞Ô∏è <strong>Constellation Technologies &amp; Operations raises ‚Ç¨9.3 million for satellite-powered 5G internet (üá´üá∑)</strong></h3><p>5G is achieving lift-off with <a href="https://www.constellation.global/">Constellation Technologies &amp; Operations</a> having raised <strong>‚Ç¨9.3 million in Seed funding</strong> from <a href="https://www.expansion-vc.eu/">Expansion</a> and the <a href="https://www.bpifrance.fr/catalogue-offres/oc-french-tech-seed">French Tech Seed fund</a>. üßë‚ÄçüöÄ Targeting telecom operators through a B2B2C model, Constellation is building a <strong>network of satellites</strong> to deliver 5G connectivity from space. They aim to make internet access universal and high quality (low-latency and high-speed). The company focuses on deploying satellites in <strong>Very Low Earth Orbit</strong>, preventing potential sustainability issues, such as light pollution and space debris. üõú</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://tech.eu/2024/10/14/constellation-technologies-operations-secures-9-3m-for-satellite-internet-access/">Constellation Technologies &amp; Operations Secures ‚Ç¨9.3M for Satellite Internet Access</a></p></blockquote><div><hr></div><h3>‚õΩÔ∏è&nbsp;Aerleum has secured ‚Ç¨5.5 million in Seed funding to scale up industrial decarbonization <strong>(üá´üá∑)</strong></h3><p>In a Seed round headed by <a href="https://www.360cap.vc/">360 Capital</a> and <a href="https://www.htgf.de/en/">HTGF</a>, climate-tech startup <a href="https://aerleum.com/">Aerleum </a>which specialises in CO‚ÇÇ capture and utilization has raised <strong>‚Ç¨5.5 million</strong>. </p><p>This funding will accelerate the industrialization of Aerleum‚Äôs innovative technology, which converts atmospheric CO‚ÇÇ and low-carbon hydrogen into synthetic fuels (e-fuels) and chemicals. They‚Äôre targeting hard-to-decarbonize industries, such as maritime, aviation, and chemicals. Aerleum plans to launch its <strong>first full-scale pilot unit</strong> and collaborate with industry players to deploy its technology. üí®</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://www.eu-startups.com/2024/10/strasbourg-based-aerleum-raises-e5-5-million-to-revolutionize-co%E2%82%82-capture-and-conversion-technology/">Strasbourg-based Aerleum Raises ‚Ç¨5.5 Million to Revolutionize CO‚ÇÇ Capture and Conversion Technology</a></p></blockquote><pre><code>üì∞ News of the week</code></pre><h3>üë©‚Äçüíª Ex-OpenAI CTO Mira Murati is raising over $100 million for her new startup </h3><p>‚Ä¶which will focus on developing <strong>proprietary AI products</strong>. üëÄ</p><p>After stepping down last month, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/mira-murati-4b39a066/">Murati</a> cited a desire to explore new opportunities. </p><p>She played a key role at <a href="https://openai.com/">OpenAI</a> since joining in 2018, later becoming CTO in 2022, and briefly serving as interim CEO during Sam Altman‚Äôs temporary ouster. Murati‚Äôs departure follows a wave of executive exits at OpenAI, which <a href="https://www.reuters.com/technology/artificial-intelligence/openai-closes-66-billion-funding-haul-valuation-157-billion-with-investment-2024-10-02/">recently raised $6.6 billion</a> in the largest VC round to date. üí∏</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://techcrunch.com/2024/10/19/former-openai-cto-mira-murati-is-reportedly-fundraising-for-a-new-ai-startup/">Former OpenAI CTO Mira Murati is Reportedly Fundraising for a New AI Startup</a></p></blockquote><div><hr></div><h3>üöÄ The Exploration Company, a SpaceX competitor, is nearing a deal to raise ‚Ç¨150 million </h3><p>Munich and Bordeaux-based space tech company, <a href="https://www.exploration.space/">The Exploration Company</a> (TEC), is reportedly close to securing <strong>‚Ç¨150 million in funding, bringing its valuation to around ‚Ç¨450 million</strong>. London-based <a href="https://www.balderton.com/">Balderton Capital</a> is expected to participate in the round, which will support TEC‚Äôs mission of building the first privately-funded <strong>reusable space capsule</strong> capable of flying to space stations and the moon.</p><p>Founded in 2021 by Airbus alumna <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/helenehuby/">H√©l√®ne Huby</a>, TEC recently made headlines when its capsule reached space aboard a <a href="https://www.esa.int/Enabling_Support/Space_Transportation/Ariane/Europe_s_new_Ariane_6_rocket_powers_into_space">French Ariane 6 rocket</a>. The company also secured a ‚Ç¨25 million contract from the European Space Agency <strong>to develop a commercial cargo service</strong> <strong>to low-Earth orbit</strong> by 2028. ü™ê</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://sifted.eu/articles/the-exploration-company-funding-round-news">SpaceX Competitor The Exploration Company Nears Deal to Raise ‚Ç¨150M in Fresh Funding</a></p></blockquote><pre><code><code>üëî Internships &amp; job offers</code></code></pre><h3>Internships</h3><p>Analyst Intern Digital West - <strong>Earlybird </strong>(Berlin)</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://earlybirdvc-gmbh.jobs.personio.de/job/1771796?language=en&amp;display=en&amp;utm_source=venturecapitalcareers#apply">‚û§&nbsp;Job  desc.</a></p></blockquote><p>VC Analyst - <strong>Alven </strong>(Paris)</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/alven-vc_join-our-investment-team-for-an-exciting-activity-7254149405971267584-CPP_?utm_source=share&amp;utm_medium=member_desktop">‚û§&nbsp;Job  desc.</a></p></blockquote><p>ESG Analyst - <strong>PAI Partners </strong>(London)</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://lnkd.in/eXV5EWiR">‚û§&nbsp;Job  desc.</a></p></blockquote><h3>Jobs</h3><p>Ventures Analyst - <strong>Plug and Play </strong>(Valencia)</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://plugandplaytechcenter.bamboohr.com/careers/1184?utm_source=venturecapitalcareers">‚û§&nbsp;Job desc.</a></p></blockquote><p>Principal - <strong>Marble</strong> (Paris)</p><blockquote><p><a href="https://marblestudio.typeform.